election_record.label: Massachusetts 1804 Electoral College

overview.note: Massachusetts law required a vote for 19 separate electors in a statewide election. Votes were required for two at-large electors and one elector each from the state's 17 congressional districts.
The Independent Chronicle (Boston, MA) and Boston Town Records use the spelling Sever for William Seaver.
Brookline Town Records uses the name Mulloon for Ebenezer Mattoon, Jr.
Ware Town Records uses the spelling Cotten Tufts for Cotton Tufts and David Rositer for David Rosseter.
Warren Town Records (formerly Western) uses the spelling Goodhew for Benjamin Goodhue.

"MAINE REPUBLICANISM, CONFIRMED--by a Majority of 2199! In the ARGUS of May 31st, we made a statement of the Votes given for Governor in the District of Maine, proving a Republican Majority of 64 votes for Judge Sullivan; this our Federal opponent declared incorrect, and promised to prove by an official statement that there was a Federal majority of about 300--but has never done it. The following is a statement of votes given at the three last important Elections, (those for Electors are official) and prove the complete triumph of Reason and Principle over Error and Faction: ... Federal Majority, in 1803, 4881; Republican Majority, in April last, 64; Republican Majority, the 5th Nov. inst. 2199; Federal Loss, in 19 months, 2272; Republican Gain in 19 months, 4808. The District of Maine has furnished about one-fifth of the Electoral Votes, and two-thirds of the Republican Majority." The Eastern Argus (Portland, ME). November 30, 1804.

sub_unit.name: York
sub_unit.note: "Cornish, Porterfield, and Lovell, in York County gave the honorable Mr. CUTTS 94 votes, and but 10 against him, they also gave 84 votes for the Republican Electors, yet no return was received at Boston from either of those towns. We hope no blame is to be attached to the Selectmen of those towns--but this negligence ought to be traced to its source, as the choice of Representative and Electors might have been destroyed, and the votes of a majority of the County rendered ineffectual." The Eastern Argus (Portland, ME). November 30, 1804.
